post_text:
MISD Families,

For students who will be attending on-site, please take a moment to read and complete the brief survey below. MISD will begin the year for students attending on-site with a 2 week hybrid schedule. Students will attend on-site 5 of the first 10 days, but breakfast/lunch will be available through your child's meal account on the days when your child is not on-site. Please complete the following survey no later than Friday, September 4 to indicate whether or not you wish to pick up breakfast/lunch for your child(ren) on the days when they are not attending on-site. Thank you!

*Survey is accessible using the link above or by entering https://forms.gle/yTFpG9Kh9neTVdv9A in your browser.

Thank you,
MISD

shared_text:
the ROAR store is feeling inspired.
August 27 at 3:32 PM ·

Support our Marion #commUNITY with the purchase of a "Stronger Together" t-shirt. All proceeds benefit, either, the Linn-Mar or Marion School District Booster Clubs. Booster Clubs around the country face shortfalls in their budgets due to the effects of COVID-19, last spring and this summer. Let's help them get back on track, and in return, enable them to continue to help our students.
https://lmmstrongertogether2020.itemorder.com/sale
*Orders due Monday, 9/14

**This project was solely designed to support our community following the storm on August 10th, and preceded by a lack of school-related activities due to COVID-19.

post_text:
Dear parents/guardians,

I write to you in the hopes that you and your loved ones are safe and are working through clean-up from Monday’s storm. This year continues to present our community with challenges. MISD remains without power, phone, or internet service. Although we are continuing to assess the extent, we have damage to several buildings. We are discussing a delay to the start of the school year as a result. More information will be coming early next week following the Board meeting Monday evening. Take care and stay safe!

Janelle Brouwer, Superintendent
text:
Dear parents/guardians,

We are discussing a delay to the start of the school year as a result. More information will be coming early next week following the Board meeting Monday evening. Take care and stay safe!

Janelle Brouwer, Superintendent

Based on feedback and to help with convenience and accessibility for families, we are adjusting the dates for serving grab and go breakfasts/lunches to Monday and Thursday only, providing multiple days of food each time. 6:30-8:30 AM (VMS only)
10-12:00 PM (Longfellow, Starry, FMI, VMS)

Breakfasts/lunches are free and open to everyone ages 1-18 regardless of free, reduced, or full price meal status.

shared_text:
Granite City Food & Brewery (Cedar Rapids)
March 16 at 4:51 PM ·

Dear Friends,
As we all know, spring break is upon us and Cedar Rapids and the surrounding school districts have closed schools temporarily in an attempt to control the spread of COVID 19 as well. We believe this is the right decision, but also understand that it may present challenges to families in the communities we serve. We'd like to help.
If you are concerned about ensuring your children have lunch, stop by or call Granite City Food and Brewery. Every kid can receive a free lunch that contains a turkey sandwich, chips, and applesauce. Completely free, no other purchase is necessary. Just ask for a manager and we will be happy to make it happen.
Valid at Granite City Food and Brewery in Cedar Rapids, IA
We are all in this together,
- Your Local Management Team

post_text:
Finding Kind - a documentary hosted by Tanager Place. March 3rd.

Tanager Place is hosting a screening of the documentary called Finding Kind – the second in our Tanager Talks series, which hopes to start conversation around mental health topics. Finding Kind is a film that tells the story of girl-against-girl bullying and its effects on one’s life as they transition into adulthood. It depicts how bullying is evolving and discusses how we can start changing this pattern; the aim is to put an end to the hate and find kind.

Parents and children, 10 years and older, are encouraged to attend this documentary screening, followed by a panel discussion. Though the film is focused on girl-against-girl bullying, the message transcends gender and all participants can benefit from the discussion.

Marion Times
January 23 at 11:30 AM ·

Indians extend win streak to 7
Brandon Leonard mariontimessports@gmail.com · January 23rd, 2020

Class 3A has been put on notice: the Marion Indians are for real. They can win in a number of ways: whether it be from late game heroics, a grind-it-out victory or a blowout. They have done all of those in less than a week as they scored victories over Beckman, Mount Vernon and Oelwein in a six day stretch.

Read the full story at http://mariontoday.org/times/article.php?id=9864

-Times Photo by Ken Gilchrist | Sports Photographer
Marion guard Cael Hodges breaks free for a shot in the second quarter against Oelwein Monday, Jan. 21, at the Red Gym in Marion. Marion won the game 66-25.

post_text: What a great day of learning for our MISD staff! Karey Chase, Senior Manager of Community Investment for United Way of East Central Iowa and RaeAnn Gordon, Director of Iowa State Extension and Outreach of Linn County presented on scarcity and trauma in our community. Also, two teams from MISD presented on Trauma Informed Responses. Those teams were Kat Bevins/Erik Trilk and Annette Maier/Jamie Shields/Kelli Johnson. Thanks everyone!

shared_text:
Marion Times
December 12, 2019 at 11:00 AM ·

Indians dispose of Raiders, CP-U
Brandon Leonard mariontimessports@gmail.com · December 12th, 2019

The first two games of the Pete Messerli era have been successes as the Marion boys basketball team has the look of a Class 3A contender with a 2-0 record. The Indians thumped Williamsburg in their home opener 65-41 on Tuesday, December 3 and cruised to a road victory over Center Point-Urbana 73-59 last Friday night. Efficient scoring and great ball movement have been the keys to their early season wins.

Read the full story at http://mariontoday.org/times/article.php?id=9781

-Times Photo by Ken Gilchrist | Sports Photographer
Gage Franck works the baseline against Center Point-Urbana during the first half at Center Point on December 6. Franck dropped in eight shots from three point range and was the leading scorer with 33 points as Marion overcame a seven point deficit at half to win the game 73-59.

post_text:
PLEASE SHARE!

Santa’s Workshop

With new owners, the northeast corner of 10th Street and 7th Avenue in Uptown Marion is coming back to life. This holiday season creates a new tradition and visit 1000 7th Avenue (the former Marion Maid-Rite location) as it is transformed into Santa’s Workshop. Community members are invited to visit with Santa and enjoy photo ops, cookies, and cocoa.

Dec. 13, 14, 20, 21

5:30-7:30 p.m.

1000 7th Avenue (former Maid-Rite Building)

In the spirit of the holiday season, event organizers will collect new, twin-sized sheet sets, mattress pads, comforters, and pillows to support the Marion chapter of Sleep in Heavenly Peace. The organization is dedicated to building, assembling, and delivering quality bunk beds to children and area families in need.
